    "model_type": "PK",
    "objective": "“to evaluate the effects of age, total body weight (TBW), patient origin (German/Spanish), sex, and comedication on LTG clearance.” And “to facilitate the optimization of treatments with LTG”",
    "covariates": "Tested: AGE, SEX, origin (German or Spanish), WT, comedication with VPA, LVT, CBZ, PHB, PHT, PRM Included: WT, VPA, PHT, PHB/PRM, CBZ, IND",
    "observations": "Variance of CL reduced from 47.5% to 27.5% using the covariates, of which most are comedication related.",
    "dose": "Steady-state oral doses in patients",
    "structure": "1 compartment with linear absorption and elimination",
    "equations": "CL/F=theta1*WT*exp(theta2*VPA)*exp(theta3*PHT)* exp(theta4*PHBPRM)*exp(theta5*CBZ)*exp(theta6*IND)*exp(eta1) Vd/F=theta7*WT Ka=theta8 F1=1 Cobs=Cipred+eps1 VPA=comedication with valproic acid (yes =1, no=0) Although their model reports covariate VPA to be modelled as exp(-theta7*VPA), their reported value for theta7 is negative. The combination of these two would lead to VPA increasing LMT clearance, while in fact it decreases it. The only logical conclusion is that either the value of theta2 should be positive, or the minus sign should be removed from exp(-theta2*VPA). Here we went for the second option PHT=comedication with phenytoin (yes =1, no=0) PHBPRM=comedication with phenobarbital OR primidone (yes =1, no=0) CBZ=comedication with carbamazepine (yes =1, no=0) IND=comedication with 2 or more inducers (yes =1, no=0)",
    "parameter_values": "theta1=0.028 theta2=-0.713 theta3=0.663 theta4=0.588 theta5=0.467 theta6=0.864 theta7=1.5 theta8=1.3 omega1= 0.07285 sigma1=1.25",
    "validation": "No / No"
